title: For Sale:  Springfield Armory M1A Super Match McMillan 7.62
location: New York, New York, United States
postcontent:
I also take trades like hunting rifles, tactical rifles, handguns and quality optics. Just email me directly at dominiclucas843@yahoo.com or use the gunbroker ask seller a question feature and tell me what you have. Maybe we can work out a trade or use it as a partial down payment.

WE DO SHIP TO CALIFORNIA! It is up to you, the buyer, to make sure this is legal in your area, and if it is we are an approved seller to the state of California and are more than happy to serve you.

We are an FFL and will accept trade-ins, shipped to us or brought in locally, from individuals. No need to pay your FFL a fee for doing it when we can walk you through the process.

Hello and thank you for checking out our auction. Up for auction is a very nice rare Springfield Armory M1A Super Match .308/7.62 sitting in a McMillan stock from the factory.

The Springfield Super Match M1A is a semi-automatic rifle chambered in 7.62 NATO or .308 Win. The M1A is a civilian version of the famous M14, which was once a standard issue US military rifle and known to be very accurate and reliable. Springfield offers eight different models of the M1A.

The Super Match is very similar to the National Match, but the difference is the Super has a Douglas air gauged heavy match barrel. Air gauged quality means designers pushed air through the barrel and measured the amount that escaped. The process determines the tolerance (or consistency of design) of the bore. It basically proves the barrel shoots accurately and keeps a tight seal on the propellant gases as they push the projectile out the bore. It also has a rear lugged receiver that increases available bedding area. With a larger bedding area, any wear is distributed to a wider body in turn less direct wear and increased lifespan.

The Super Match is gas-operated, so propellant gases are captured by a tube near the muzzle, which directs the gas into a valve on the bolt, and the gas pushes the bolt back so it can eject a spent casing and chamber a fresh round.

Its features include a national match two-stage trigger that sets off the action with a 4.5- to 5-pound pull. A match hooded rear sight aperture thatâs like looking through a pinhole. Itâs also adjustable for windage and elevation. It has a fixed blade front sight. The national match flash suppressor helps reduce muzzle climb, so the shooter can stay on target after every shot. The barrel rests on a glass bedding, which acts as an intermediary so when the barrel heats and swells it will press against the bedding instead of the stock. The Super Match is also available with either a matte black barrel or a stainless steel one.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Vz. 24 8mm Mauser w/ bayonet
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a Vz. 24 Mauser, chambered in 7.92x57mm (aka 8mm Mauser).  It was produced by the Czechs on contract for Romania in 1940.  All of the metal parts have been reblued at postwar arsenal refurbishment with a deep bluing.  The royal Romanian receiver crest was scrubbed by the Communists after the war, but the outer edges of the original crest are just visible on the receiver ring. The stock serial number matches the receiver, and the bolt has been electropenciled by the arsenal during refurb to match.

It has a PW Arms import mark on the side of the barrel. The stock is a lighter replacement stock installed during the refurb and is in excellent condition, while the handguard is the darker original wood with the bumps and bruises of heavy use but no cracks. The bore is shiny, with some slight frosting. It is an excellent shooter. The original reblued extractor had issues, so it has been replaced with an "in the white" extractor that functions perfectly.

Also included is a similarly refurbed Vz. 24 bayonet with sheath. 

Note that the rifle will not include the reproduction Czech-style sling shown in these photos. 

Additional higher resolution photos are available by email.

$325 cash, or I'm looking to trade for one of the items listed below (+/- cash as needed).  I will also consider trades for other military surplus firearms or 9mm/45 handguns.  I'm only interested in original configuration military surplus rifles; no cut down or sporterized examples please.

title: For Sale:  AR-15
postcontent:
First of all, if you do just a little research, the Feinstein bill has about a 0% chance of passing the House of Reps (and a very low chance of passing the Senate if it actually arrived there). An assault weapon ban is just not going to happen.

With that said, the people that are still re-selling ARs on here for 2X their value, is getting old. Which is perfectly legal, and fine with me. But don't come on here and try to justify what you're doing, especially when terms/phrases such as "market value", "supply and demand" are used, when it is obvious that the seller has never taken a general economics class. 
Using a little logic and common sense, I will walk way out on a limb and venture to say that the prices of these rifles will decrease quite a bit over the next 6-12 months, after the credit cards are maxed out and the rate of supply overtakes the rate of demand. 

I always thought it was a universally shared rule of thumb that after an individual buys a brand new firearm (assuming it is in new condition), the maximum price they should sell it for is the total price paid minus the sales tax. When a gun leaves the store, it is automatically worth less than what the dealer sold it for. The private seller is not a dealer running a business; a profit does not have to be made. Just sell the item for the price is it worth.

Anyway, to those of you trying to make profits off of this "situation"...just post your overpriced gun, and leave it at that. Trying to justify what you're doing, making yourself feel better, less guilty, etc., is a losing battle and it makes you look pathetic.
